│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash is an assertion in APInt construction: APInt(BitWidth, NumElements) │
│ where BitWidth is derived from the index type. In the reproducer, the index   │
│ is an i1, and the vector has 16 elements. Constructing APInt(1, 16) violates  │
│ the invariant that the value must fit within BitWidth bits, triggering the    │
│ assertion.                                                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ In terms of legality, if the index type cannot represent values up to         │
│ NumElements-1, then all possible values of the index are necessarily          │
│ in-bounds (since the maximum representable index is less than NumElements).   │
│ Therefore, scalarization should be considered safe. The current code attempts │
│ to build a ConstantRange [0, NumElements) in the width of the index type even │
│ when NumElements does not fit, causing the crash.                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The debug log shows the pass visiting load, insertelement, and store, then    │
│ immediately hitting the assertion in canScalarizeAccess during                │
│ foldSingleElementStore. No transformations were printed before the crash,     │
│ confirming the first transformation point is canScalarizeAccess.              │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In canScalarizeAccess, after handling constant indices, the code computes:    │
│ - IntWidth from Idx->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits()                         │
│ - APInt Zero(IntWidth, 0)                                                     │
│ - APInt MaxElts(IntWidth, NumElements)                                        │
│ If NumElements does not fit into IntWidth (e.g., NumElements=16, IntWidth=1), │
│ APInt constructor asserts because val exceeds the width capacity. This is an  │
│ unhandled case where the index type cannot represent all in-bounds values;    │
│ logically, such indices are always safe, but the code crashes while building  │
│ the range to prove it.                                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ We should add an early guard immediately after handling the constant-index    │
│ case and before constructing APInts. If the index bitwidth is smaller than    │
│ the bits needed to represent NumElements-1 (i.e., NumElements > 2^IntWidth),  │
│ then any representable index is in-range, so we can return                    │
│ ScalarizationResult::safe() and skip APInt construction entirely.             │
│ Additionally, we must only construct APInt(MaxElts) when NumElements fits     │
│ within IntWidth to avoid the assertion.                                       │
│                                                                               │
│ Concrete change at lines 1446-1453 in                                         │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp:                              │
│ - After the constant-index check, compute IntWidth.                           │
│ - If IntWidth < 64 and NumElements >= (1ULL << IntWidth), return              │
│ ScalarizationResult::safe(). This avoids overflow and handles all small-width │
│ cases (including i1).                                                         │
│ - Then proceed to create APInt Zero/MaxElts only when NumElements fits; this  │
│ is the existing path.                                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ This preserves correctness for scalable vectors because NumElements is the    │
│ known minimum; if the minimum already exceeds the representable range, all    │
│ indices of that type are in-bounds for the minimum, making scalarization safe │
│ under our check.                                                              │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The fix prevents constructing an APInt with a value that doesn't fit the      │
│ specified bitwidth by recognizing that indices of narrower integer types are  │
│ inherently in-bounds when NumElements exceeds the type's range. This resolves │
│ the crash and maintains the intended legality checks in canScalarizeAccess.   │
│ The expected effect is that the reproducer will no longer assert, and         │
│ vector-combine will correctly classify the i1 index case as safe for          │
│ scalarization.                                                                │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
