  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash is an assertion in APInt
construction: APInt(BitWidth, NumElements) where BitWidth is derived from the
index type. In the reproducer, the index is an i1, and the vector has 16
elements. Constructing APInt(1, 16) violates the invariant that the value must
fit within BitWidth bits, triggering the assertion.\n\nIn terms of legality, if
the index type cannot represent values up to NumElements-1, then all possible
values of the index are necessarily in-bounds (since the maximum representable
index is less than NumElements). Therefore, scalarization should be considered
safe. The current code attempts to build a ConstantRange [0, NumElements) in the
width of the index type even when NumElements does not fit, causing the
crash.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows the pass visiting load,
insertelement, and store, then immediately hitting the assertion in
canScalarizeAccess during foldSingleElementStore. No transformations were printed
before the crash, confirming the first transformation point is
canScalarizeAccess.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn canScalarizeAccess, after
handling constant indices, the code computes:\n- IntWidth from
Idx->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits()\n- APInt Zero(IntWidth, 0)\n- APInt
MaxElts(IntWidth, NumElements)\nIf NumElements does not fit into IntWidth (e.g.,
NumElements=16, IntWidth=1), APInt constructor asserts because val exceeds the
width capacity. This is an unhandled case where the index type cannot represent
all in-bounds values; logically, such indices are always safe, but the code
crashes while building the range to prove it.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe
should add an early guard immediately after handling the constant-index case and
before constructing APInts. If the index bitwidth is smaller than the bits needed
to represent NumElements-1 (i.e., NumElements > 2^IntWidth), then any
representable index is in-range, so we can return ScalarizationResult::safe() and
skip APInt construction entirely.\nAdditionally, we must only construct
APInt(MaxElts) when NumElements fits within IntWidth to avoid the
assertion.\n\nConcrete change at lines 1446-1453 in
llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp:\n- After the constant-index
check, compute IntWidth.\n- If IntWidth < 64 and NumElements >= (1ULL <<
IntWidth), return ScalarizationResult::safe(). This avoids overflow and handles
all small-width cases (including i1).\n- Then proceed to create APInt
Zero/MaxElts only when NumElements fits; this is the existing path.\n\nThis
preserves correctness for scalable vectors because NumElements is the known
minimum; if the minimum already exceeds the representable range, all indices of
that type are in-bounds for the minimum, making scalarization safe under our
check.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe fix prevents constructing an APInt with a value
that doesn't fit the specified bitwidth by recognizing that indices of narrower
integer types are inherently in-bounds when NumElements exceeds the type's range.
This resolves the crash and maintains the intended legality checks in
canScalarizeAccess. The expected effect is that the reproducer will no longer
assert, and vector-combine will correctly classify the i1 index case as safe for
scalarization.",
